               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18640201-name-147" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-147" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-147" type="surname" value="SHEPHERD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-147" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD SHEPHERD</persName>
                  </hi>. I am registrar of British ships for the Port of Londonâ€”I have here a copy, certified by myself, of the register of the <hi rend="italic">Flowery Land</hi> (<hi rend="italic">This described the vessel as the Flowery Land, of the Port of London, and the owner as William Weemys Kerr, of 25, Poultry, in the City of London, merchant.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18640201-name-148" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-148" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-148" type="surname" value="TAFFER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-148" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM TAFFER</persName>
                  </hi>. I was second mate on board the British ship the <hi rend="italic">Flowery Land</hi>â€”she left the Port of London on 28th July, last yearâ€”the captain's name was John Smithâ€”he had a brother, George Smith, who was</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010044"></xptr>
               <p>a passenger on boardâ€”the name of the first mate was John Carswellâ€”the steward's name was <hi rend="italic">Aboo</hi>â€”he was a Malayâ€”the cook was a Chinaman; I do not know his nameâ€”there was also a boy who attended to the lamps; I don't know his name, but we called him <hi rend="italic">Cassa</hi>â€”Michael Anderson was the carpenterâ€”there was a Frenchman, an able seaman, called Candereauâ€”the prisoners were all seamen, able or ordinary, on boardâ€”some short time after sailing there were some complaints by the captain about some of these men being deficient in their dutyâ€”I never saw the captain use any violenceâ€”I have heard him call them names, "<hi rend="italic">Coolies</hi>," and "Sons of bitches"â€”the men complained about the food and water, which was attended to directly and rectifiedâ€”I heard Blanco make one complaint, and that was attended toâ€”he did not think that the scale of victualling and articles was enough, and wanted moreâ€”I remember about the commencement of September Carlos being wanted on deckâ€”the mate and I went and asked him several times to come on deckâ€”he would not come, and the mate took hold of him and pulled him out of his berthâ€”he said he was sick, and wanted his watch belowâ€”all the watch stopped below with himâ€”they were Marcelino, Marco, Watter, Blanco, and Chaucis (<hi rend="italic">Lopez</hi>), Carlos, and two others; I don't re<lb></lb>member their namesâ€”the mate and I brought Carlos <hi rend="italic">aft</hi> on to the quarter<lb></lb>deckâ€”all the rest turned to their work but Carlosâ€”he would not turn to, and the mate ordered me to bind him fast to the riggingâ€”I made him fast, and he remained bound for about five minutesâ€”the captain then came up out of the cabin, and inquired what was the matter, and gave me orders to loose him, and he gave him some medicine, and he went below and turned into his berth for the dayâ€”some days afterwards I remember a quarrel between Carlos and Blancoâ€”I and the mate interfered to stop them from fightingâ€”the mate and Carlos struggled together, and the mate gave him a blow; I can't say for certain where, but he gave him one, I thinkâ€”I re<lb></lb>member the night that the captain was killedâ€”I had the first watch, from 8 to 12â€”Mr. Carswell, the chief mate, relieved me at 12â€”his watch lasted from 12 till 4 in the morningâ€”when I was relieved I turned inâ€”there is a house on deck, divided into four compartmentsâ€”the prisoners lodged in one compartment, on the port side; the fore compartment; not all the crew; these eight prisoners, and Powell and Williamsâ€”those ten occupied the fore compartment, on the port sideâ€”on the starboard side, were the carpenter, Candereau, a seaman, and the boy Earlyâ€”on the starboard side aft was the cook's galley, and on the port side aft the boatswain's storeâ€”on going down the companion ladder, the first berth on the port side was the mate's; the next was the captain's brother, and the next aft was mineâ€”the captain occupied all the starboard side himselfâ€”the main cabin was between, with a sky-light opening on to the poopâ€”I turned in at 12 o'clock the night the captain was killedâ€”I was awoke by a noise on deck, about 3 o'clockâ€”it was a noise like a beating or hammering on the companionâ€”I instantly ran out of my berth and tried to get on deck to see what was wrongâ€”I could not get on deck for some person lying on his face on the companion ladder, with his head parallel with the top stepâ€”a number of persons were beating him on the head with hand-spikes or capstan barsâ€”I recognised one of them to be Blancoâ€”at the same time I received a blow that hurled me right down the companion again into the cabinâ€”I took hold of the man they were beating, and tried to pull him away, but I was not able to move himâ€”I then called out to the captain for assistance, but got no answerâ€”I went into his berth, and found that he was goneâ€”I then went into the main cabin; I trimmed the light, which was very dim, and I found</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010045"></xptr>
               <p>the captain lying dead, and a pool of blood round himâ€”his night dress was all full of cuts on the left sideâ€”I then went into the captain's brother's berthâ€”I found him gone alsoâ€”I next went back to the companion, and examined the man who was lying in the companion, and found it to be the captain's brother by his dressâ€”I then went into my berth, and locked the doorâ€”the noise was going on all this time, for about three-quarters of an hourâ€”the noise ceased about five minutes after I went into my berth, and they kept calling me several times on deckâ€”it was some of the men; who it was I don't know; I did not recognise their voicesâ€”at the end of about three-quarters of an hour a great many of these men came down in the cabinâ€”Lyons was spokesman; there was Blanco, Duranno, Santos, Chancis (Lopez), and Carlos, and some othersâ€”the parties that I have mentioned circled round my cabinâ€”there were some behind themâ€”I could not see who they were, but these I am sure ofâ€”Lyons called me out of my berthâ€”I asked him what he was going to do with me; if he was going to kill meâ€”he answered noâ€”he said they had killed the captain and the mate, and the captain's brother had got away somewhere; they did not know whereâ€”he said, "I do not know where"â€”he meant to say that he had got away somewhere, or stowed awayâ€”he did not say they had killed him; he had got away from them, or something to that effect.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Just say again what he said about killing the captain and the mate? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He said they had killed the captain and the mate.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> If he spoke to you he would, I suppose, say "we" or "I," what words did he use? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Well, I think, he used "we."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. GIFFARD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What next? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> They wished me to navigate the vessel to some place so that they could get on shoreâ€”I asked him where I was to navigate her toâ€”I understood from him that there was nobody on board that knew anything about navigation; none of these menâ€”the other prisoners were all in the main cabin at the time Lyons spoke to me; they were all close to him; within hearingâ€”I had opened my door, and come out at this timeâ€”all the prisoners were near enough to hear what Lyons saidâ€”I mean those that I have mentioned; Blanco, Duranno, Lopez, Watter, Carlos, and Santosâ€”I asked where I was to navigate the ship toâ€”Carlos told me to the River Plate or Buenos Ayresâ€”Carlos spoke in English when he told me thatâ€”he said it was a good country, and plenty of Spanish people thereâ€”that was all that passed then about navigating the vesselâ€”the ship was then 19 south and 36 westâ€”the next thing I saw was Marco Watto with a rope round the captain's neck, in the act to haul his body up out of the cabinâ€”I begged of him to allow me to sew him up in canvas, as I did not like to see his body going overboard like thatâ€”he allowed me to do so, and I sewed him upâ€”I went on deck about 5 in the morningâ€”I saw Santos when I went upâ€”I passed him on the deckâ€”he was armed with a large knife, and he put his hand on it in a very threatening mannerâ€”about 8 in the morning all hands were mustered in the cabinâ€”all hands came into the cabin, with the exception, I think, of the man at the wheel; I don't know who that wasâ€”Lyons spoke in English to me, and said the men wished to have free access to the captain's berth; they wanted to see what money and clothes he had gotâ€”the chief actors in gathering up the money were Blanco, Lopez, Watter, and Carlos; the others were sitting round about in the cabin, but I can't remember what they were busy aboutâ€”they rummaged all the boxes and desksâ€”when the only was all gathered up it was put on the table in the main cabinâ€”Lyons told me to share it into seventeen partsâ€”Watter objected to that, and mentioned eightâ€”he speaks some few words</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010046"></xptr>
               <p>in English, but he spoke in Spanishâ€”I understand a little Spanishâ€”I ob<lb></lb>jected to divide it out; I said I did not want to have any share in itâ€”Lyons said I should have a share in it, and to divide it out amongst themâ€”I objected to do it, and said they could do it without me, but Lyons insisted that I should do it, and I shared it out in seventeen partsâ€”I put my share into the writing-desk, and never saw it afterâ€”the four that were the chief actors in gathering up the money gathered out the clothes as wellâ€”they did not ask me to divide them; every one took what they liked; I don't know exactly who took them; all that were in the cabin, I believe; I did not take much notice of what they didâ€”I saw the captain's watch put into the writing-desk where I put my money; I don't remember who put it thereâ€”they put it there, they said, to sell it afterwards, they could not divide itâ€”I saw chests of boots and shoes broken open, and each took what they liked out of themâ€”I do not remember who helped themselves to those; I don't remember any names; all that were down thereâ€”they had not left the cabinâ€”I don't know what became of the cap<lb></lb>tain's brotherâ€”the cargo consisted of bottled beer, wine, iron pipes, and bale goodsâ€”there was some champagne; that was broachedâ€”I saw cases of it knocking about the deck, and bottles of it, and all sorts of cloth and merchandiseâ€”who were the actors then I don't knowâ€”some few days after this had happened we saw a ship standing in the same course that we wereâ€”I asked Lyons if I might speak to her, as I wished to compare longitudeâ€”he said he did not think these men would allow me to speak to any vessel or hoist any signal, but he would go forward and speak to them, and see if they would allow meâ€”he went forward, and came aft and said I might speak to her, but not to say anything about what had occurredâ€”I steered towards the ship and spoke to her; she turned out to be an English ship from Liverpool, called <hi rend="italic">The Friends</hi>, bound to Buenos Ayresâ€”Carlos told me to say the ship's name was <hi rend="italic">Louisa</hi>, and not to say where we came from, or where we were bound toâ€”I gave the ship's name as <hi rend="italic">Louisa</hi>, from New Dieppe, bound to Valparaiso, forty-seven days outâ€”I did that because I was afraid for my life; I gave that fictitious name because I was afraid if I did otherwise I should meet with the same fate as the captain and the mateâ€”the other men were all on the quarter-deck at the timeâ€”after <hi rend="italic">The Friends</hi> had passed there was a great noise amongst these Manilla men, the Spaniards, and two Greeksâ€”they were talking in Spanishâ€”I could not understand them properly, but they looked very threatening, as if they were dissatisfied about somethingâ€”Lyons told me that those who did not understand English thought I had told all about what had occurredâ€”they did not actually do anything, but they were standing talking to one another, and casting very threatening looks at meâ€”I remember on 30th September Watter being on deck; he took a knife to the steward, and cut him through the fleshy part of the arm, and put a cut in his right side about three inches long and half an inch deepâ€”next day I was called in to the steward's berthâ€”Blanco, Watter, Chancis, and Lyons were standing outside the door; Duranno was also thereâ€”I had got the steward to get all the captain's papers into his berth for safetyâ€”he had done so, and they were tearing them up and heaving them overboardâ€”the steward was a Malayâ€”they asked me if I knew anything about the papers and the gold watchâ€”I said, "No"â€”Chan<lb></lb>cis spokeâ€”he said they were looking for the gold watch they had lostâ€”I told him I did not know anything about the watchâ€”we made land on the morning of 2<hi rend="italic">d</hi> Octoberâ€”we were about ten miles from land when we first sighted itâ€”when we sighted land I could not get the crew to speak to me;</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010047"></xptr>
               <p>they did not seem as if they required my services any moreâ€”they tacked the ship and stood off all dayâ€”when they had got about thirty or forty miles from land they scuttled the shipâ€”about 8 o'clock at night Blanco came down into the cabin, and ordered me on deckâ€”when I came up on deck I found they were <hi rend="italic">clewing</hi> up the sails and getting the boats overâ€”I asked Lyons what he was going to do with the shipâ€”he would not speak to meâ€”about ten minutes afterwards Marcelino passed close to meâ€”I asked him what they were going to do to-night, or if they were going to kill meâ€”he said he was not, but he thought Blanco wasâ€”that was all that passed thenâ€”about three-quarters of an hour after that I got into the boatâ€”there was the cook, the steward, Frank Powell, Watter, and the boy Early; that was all that were in that boatâ€”the other part of the crew were some on board and some in the boat astern of the ship, made fast to the shipâ€”the boat in which I was pulled away from the ship, about a hundred yardsâ€”we were called back by somebody from the ship; I could not recognise the voiceâ€”Powell, the cook, Early, and Watter were pullingâ€”nobody in the boat wished to go back with the exception of Watter; he ordered Powell to pull the boat's head round, which Powell did not wish to do, and Watter used he oar to him and made him do soâ€”the boat was then pulled back alongside the shipâ€”Lyons spoke in English, and ordered us to come on deckâ€”I did soâ€”when I got on deck I saw Lyons and Duranno throwing bottles of champagne down into the boatâ€”I heard the steward singing out some time afterwards in the water; he was singing out-to Lyons for helpâ€”he was in the water swimmingâ€”he never came ashoreâ€”I then went into the boat asternâ€”I was ordered in by Lyons and Blancoâ€”I stayed there about an hour and a halfâ€”several things were passed into the boat, but by whom I don't know; it was dark, and I could not seeâ€”after that hour and a half Lyons, Duranno, Chancis, and Blanco got into the boat; they were the last to leave the shipâ€”the others were in the other boat; some were in the boat with me while these four men were on boardâ€”I saw the ship go down; she went down the very minute these men left herâ€”I did not see the cook land ashore, or the lamp-trimmer, Cassaâ€”we steered for land, our smaller boat being towed by the larger oneâ€”we landed at 4, P.M. on 3<hi rend="italic">d</hi> Octoberâ€”when we landed Lopez said I was to say it was an American ship from Peru, laden with guano, for Bordeaux, in France; and that she had foundered 500 miles out at sea, and that they had been in the boats five days and five nights; that the captain and the other sailors had got into another boat, and we had lost them during a heavy breeze of wind, and which way they went they did not knowâ€”I did not state that to anybody; I never got anybody to inquire of me; there was no one to speak English toâ€”that night we stopped at a farm-house of a man named Corria; he afterwards drove me to a place called Rochaâ€”that was on the 5thâ€”I found out that there was a man in the camp who could talk English; that was some miles distantâ€”I and Can<lb></lb>derean got into a cartâ€”we found a person named Manuel Ramos, a store<lb></lb>keeper, who could speak Englishâ€”we had to go twenty-one milesâ€”none of the prisoners knew I was going, nobody but Candereauâ€”we made a com<lb></lb>munication to Ramosâ€”after that I went before the Naval Court at Monte Video.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. TINDAL ATKINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was the captain, when he left England, in the habit of drinking a good deal? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Not a great dealâ€”he was not a temperate man, still he did not drink to any excessâ€”there was a complaint made to the captain about the want of waterâ€”they were allowed three buckets a dayâ€”Blanco made a complaint</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010048"></xptr>
               <p>about the quantity of water allowedâ€”I did not hear the captain say, "Drink salt water then"â€”the watch on deck were allowed the privilege of sleeping under a sail on deck when we did not want them, so that they could lie down and rest themselves thereâ€”they were supposed to be always handy, but sometimes they would not be awakened all night in warm weatherâ€”I never heard them complain that they were not permitted to sleep in their berths, but were compelled to sleep under this sailâ€”Lyons was the man that spoke the best English on board; next to him Carlosâ€”I am not aware whether Carlos usually talked Spanish among the crew; I think they always received our orders in English; they always understood us in Englishâ€”Lyons and Powell gave them orders in Englishâ€”the orders were given to Lyons and Powell by the captain, the first mate, and myself, and by them translated to the othersâ€”that practice continued after the death of the captain, as far as the navigation of the vessel was concernedâ€”when I wanted to communicate anything to the crew I communicated to Lyons.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> After you heard this dull sound of something going on on deck, when you saw the parties there, you say you saw Lyons; had he not a cut across the face, and was he not bleeding very severely? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; that was next morning, when he came down to call me out of my berthâ€”that was the first time I saw him after the death of the captainâ€”I did not see him go on deck afterwards to have his face dressedâ€”it was a severe cut; he was bleeding very muchâ€”when I came out they said they were not going to hurt meâ€”I remember going to Lyons and putting my hand on his shoulder; I rested my hopes upon himâ€”I cannot decide upon which of the words he used, whether he said they had killed the captain or" <hi rend="italic">we</hi> have killed the captain"â€”he spoke to me in Englishâ€”I can't say which it wasâ€”everything I had got to say relating to the crew or the navigation of the ship I always communi<lb></lb>cated to Lyonsâ€”I could not say that amongst the men who took possession of the vessel there was any one man more prominent than anotherâ€”I don't know anything about where they slept at nightsâ€”I never came on deck of a night unless they came and called me, or there was something serious that wanted me on deckâ€”sometimes they used to come down and sleep in the cabinâ€”when we sighted <hi rend="italic">The Friends</hi>, and the men looked threateningly at me, Lyons interfered between me and them, and seemed to be explaining to them, so as to shelter me from their anger; I understood so by his looks, but he was talking in Spanishâ€”I believe he was doing so, and I believe he suc<lb></lb>ceededâ€”he was the principal assistant to me in the navigation of the shipâ€”I do not recollect, on leaving the ship, saying to him, "Do you want to kill me, <hi rend="italic">Joe</hi>," nor his replying, "No, certainly not, we have been like brothers together"â€”it was he who ordered me into the boat asternâ€”he showed every anxiety to save my life; and I have not the slightest doubt but that he did save my life.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was the first mate harsh with the men at all? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; not very harshâ€”it was not he who tied Carlos up; I did, by his ordersâ€”he had previously pulled him out of his berthâ€”he was a strict man, but we had to be strictâ€”he wanted his work done, of courseâ€”I never saw him use any violence; I have heard him use violent expressions.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DALEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What countryman is Lyons? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I understand he belongs to some small island close to Manillaâ€”I don't know whether he is a Moorâ€”I don't think he is an Englishmanâ€”he does not speak English grammatically; he can speak pretty good Englishâ€”I should call it broken English, as a foreigner would speak itâ€”at the time he said,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010049"></xptr>
               <p>"They," or "We have murdered the captain" he spoke in Englishâ€”I don't remember that Duranno made any observation to me at that time.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KEMP</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> I believe Santos is one of those men who cannot speak English? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yesâ€”the men were divided into two watchesâ€”all the prisoners were not in the same watchâ€”Santos was in my watchâ€”I should think it was about an hour after I went back into my cabin before I got on deckâ€”when the money was divided in the cabin all the crew were present except the man at the wheelâ€”I don't know whether Santos was the one at the wheel; I do not recollect who was at the wheelâ€”I cannot undertake to say that Santos was in the cabin at that time; my memory does not enable to say for certainâ€”the English portion of the crew did not receive different rations from the others; they were all treated exactly the same.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was any distinction made either in speaking of the men, or in addressing them, between the blacks and the other men? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; they were never styled "blacks"â€”all that I heard the captain call them was" coolies "and" sons of bitches"â€”I suppose coolies would be termed blacksâ€”I don't remember who he was addressing when he so styled themâ€”the quarrel between Carlos and Blanco was after Carlos had been tied up to the mast; I don't remember how long afterâ€”it was not a severe struggle between themâ€”the mate and I interfered, and stopped themâ€”they had not time to struggle much; one had got a knife, and the other a hand-spikeâ€”I don't know what it was aboutâ€”I don't remember ever seeing Carlos quarrelling with any of the other cooliesâ€”I cannot say it did not occur, because I did not see it to my knowledgeâ€”the captain used to talk to the coolies in Spanishâ€”I don't know what language they spoke among themselvesâ€”Spanish was the general language that was spoken on board amongst themâ€”Carlos slept in the same compartment with the blacks; I have seen him thereâ€”I never heard of his objecting to sleep there; not that I rememberâ€”I never remember his speaking to me about itâ€”he did not tell me that he did not wish to sleep in the same compartment with the blacksâ€”he was not in my watchâ€”I won't say he did not complain, but not to me that I know ofâ€”I have been about eight years at seaâ€”white men do generally object very strongly to be put in the same compartment with the blacksâ€”I do not remember that Carlos very seriously objected to being put in the same compartment with them after his quarrel with Blancoâ€”the captain was pretty kind to Carlosâ€”he exhibited great humanity on the occasion of his being tied up; he desired him to be taken down from the mastâ€”he was not tied up; he was standing quite comfortableâ€”he was tied to somethingâ€”the captain desired him to be be loosed, and to turn in, and to have medicine given to himâ€”I don't remember that the captain's brother was kind to himâ€”I never saw him show any kindness to himâ€”I left the watch on deck at 12 o'clockâ€”I do not know whether Carlos was at the wheel at that timeâ€”I never took particular noticeâ€”it was Carlos who told me to go to the River Plate or Buenos Ayresâ€”that was on the morning of the 10th of Septemberâ€”he told me that in the cabin, close to my berth door, the morning that the captain was murdered, after I had been three-quarters of an hour shut up in my berthâ€”it was dark at that time; it was not quite day-light, justâ€”I don't remember how many men were down there; I have mentioned how many I sawâ€”I was very much alarmed and excitedâ€”I am sure it was at that time that Carlos told me to go to the River Plateâ€”he told me to go to the River Plate, that it was a good country, and there were plenty of Spanish people thereâ€”I mean to say that</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010050"></xptr>
               <p>he told me that in the cabin that morningâ€”I remember his speaking to me about it on one other occasion on the quarter-deck; I don't remember how many days it was after the 10th September, I am sure it was not Lyons who told me to go to the River Plateâ€”I remember saying to Carlos, after something had been said about Buenos Ayres, "If we go there, I shall be punished first, as I am in the command of the ship"â€”I don't remember the date of the month that I said that; it was some days after the 10th; it was after they had requested me to navigate the vessel; it was said on the quarter-deck; I believe we were aloneâ€”I don't remember that he was then complaining about the blacks; he might have done soâ€”he said that Buenos Ayres was a good place to land, and all that, because there were no English authorities there, or anything of the sortâ€”I don't think I said, "I shall be punished first if we go there;" if I did say so just now, I did not under<lb></lb>stand youâ€”I remember Carlos saying something like, "No, we shan't be punished, as we had nothing whatever to do with the murder"â€”I might have used words to the effect that if we went there I should be punished first, as I was in command of the shipâ€”Carlos might have mentioned in reply, "No, we shall not be punished, as we had nothing whatever to do with the murder;" I can't give you a decided answer whether he did or not; I had too much to think aboutâ€”I can't say yes or no, whether he did say soâ€”I went ashore in the boat with Carlos after we left the vesselâ€”if Carlos was in the other boat which left the vessel, and then went back, I did not see himâ€”it was Carlos who told me to call the ship the <hi rend="italic">Louisa</hi>â€”he was then on the quarter-deckâ€”some of the blacks were there; I don't say that they were close to himâ€”they were within a few paces of him, within hearingâ€”I don't know whether they had been speaking to him before he told me that; I was looking at the ship; I don't know whether he came by their orders or not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. GIFFARD</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have mentioned that a number of men came down on the morning of the 10th, and Lyons asked you to navigate the vessel? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yesâ€”I did not direct the ship's course for Buenos Ayres exactly that day; at least I did not do so directly; I did it that dayâ€”we were originally bound for Singaporeâ€”on the morning of that day Carlos told me to navigate the ship for the River Plateâ€”he spoke to me afterwards about its being a good place to land, but I can't say how long afterwards; it was some days; I don't recollect his words exactlyâ€”he was talking about the place; that it was a good place; that there were no English people there, they were all Spanish, and they could get away, or something of that sortâ€”I don't remember what I said in answer; I very likely agreed to his words thenâ€”it did not matter what they said to me, I said yes to itâ€”the quarrel between Blanco and Carlos, when the mate and I interfered, was about 1st Septemberâ€”that quarrel had nothing to do with Carlos being tied up; the quarrel was some days after that.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18640201-name-149" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-149" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-149" type="surname" value="EARLY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-149" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>JAMES EARLY</persName>
                  </hi>. I shipped on board the <hi rend="italic">Flowery Land</hi> as ship's boy, in London in July lastâ€”the prisoners were part of the crewâ€”they also shipped from Londonâ€”I remember the morning of 10th Septemberâ€”about 2 o'clock that morning I was on the look-out on the forecastleâ€”Mr. Cars<lb></lb>well, the chief mate, was walking on a bridge that came from the poop to the forecastleâ€”I heard him sing out, "Murder"â€”I saw Duranno near himâ€”(<hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DALEY</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">submitted that as the indictment upon which the prisoners were being tried was for the murder of the captain, any inquiry as to what happened to the mate was irrelevant to this inquiry.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BARON BRAMWELL</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">considered it was important, as tending to show the existence of a common</hi>
               </p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010051"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">design</hi>)â€”Duranno was striking the chief mate with a hand-spikeâ€”I went and spoke to the mate, and the mate told me to go and call the captainâ€”Duranno heard the mate speak to me, and he told me to go into the houseâ€”he struck him again when I told him to come awayâ€”I was going to call the captain, but he stopped me, and told me to go into the houseâ€”that was the house on deckâ€”I went in, and called the carpenterâ€”the carpenter went out, and stopped about five minutesâ€”he then came back again, and said that one of the men had struck himâ€”after that he and I remained in the deck-houseâ€”about half an hour afterwards Watter came down and called Can<lb></lb>dereau, the Frenchman, out of his bedâ€”he was in his bed at the timeâ€”I saw Watter; he had a capstan-bar in his handâ€”he told Candereau to come on deck, and take the wheelâ€”Candereau said it was not 4 o'clock; he would not come on deck; the time of his watch had not arrivedâ€”he went on deck along with Watterâ€”Watter made him go; he was standing in the house inside the doorâ€”I don't know what made Candereau go, except that he was afraid of Watter; he was standing there with the capstan<lb></lb>bar in his handâ€”Candereau went on deck with Watter; I don't know whether he went to the wheel or notâ€”I went on deck about half-past 5 or 6; I don't recollect exactlyâ€”Andersen, the carpenter, went on deck with meâ€”I saw blood on the main-deck, and blood beside the cabin doorâ€”I went down into the cabin, and saw the captain's body lying thereâ€”it was wrapped up in canvas at that timeâ€”I saw Taffer, the second mate, sitting in the cabinâ€”Lyons was speaking to him; Taffer was sitting crying, and Lyons and several of the other prisoners were with himâ€”there were Chancis and Watter, and othersâ€”Lyons was telling the second mate that he must navigate the ship to where they wanted to go, and the second mate said he would do it if he couldâ€”they said they wanted to go to the River Plate, close to Buenos Ayres, and he told them he would go there if they would spare his lifeâ€”that was all I heard them sayâ€”I saw Chancis put a rope round the captain's bodyâ€”I did not see anybody help himâ€”I don't remember what part of the body he put the rope round, under the arms I thinkâ€”he sung out to them on deck to pull up, and they pulled it up out of the cabin, and <hi rend="italic">throwed</hi> it overboard; that was the last I saw of itâ€”I was standing beside the wheel that morning, and Blanco called me down into the cabin; he said they were going to share out the moneyâ€”when I got into the cabin, I found there all the crew, except the one at the wheel; I do not recollect who was left at the wheelâ€”the money was lying on the cabin table, and there was one watch or twoâ€”I do not recollect whether there were two or not, but I saw oneâ€”Taffer was there, and I heard Lyons tell him that he was to share out the money in seventeen sharesâ€”he said, no, he did not want to have anything to do with the moneyâ€”Lyons told him that the rest of the men wished him to share out the moneyâ€”Watter said it was only to be shared among eightâ€”Lyons said that they should all have a shareâ€”I got a shareâ€”I had 4<hi rend="italic">l;</hi> 1<hi rend="italic">l</hi>. 10<hi rend="italic">s</hi>. was in money, and the rest was in moidoresâ€”I saw nothing of the body of the captain's brother; I never saw it at all from that nightâ€”I never saw the chief mate after I went into the deck-houseâ€”I heard Blanco say that he was singing out for the second mate in the water when he was thrown overboardâ€”he said so that morningâ€”he said when he throwed him overboard, he was singing out in the water for the second mateâ€”About three weeks after that we made the landâ€”I remember the boats being got ready to go off; I assisted in getting them readyâ€”I saw the first boat that went over the side of shipâ€”the second mate, the steward and cook, Watter, Powell, and myself, got into that boatâ€”when we got into the boat,</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010052"></xptr>
               <p>we pushed a little way from the ship, I took one of the oars, and rowed offâ€”when we had got some distance from the ship, the party that was in the other boat began to sing out to us to come back, and we came backâ€”the other boat was then fastened to the ship; some of the crew were in the boat, and some on the shipâ€”when our boat went back to the ship, the second mate and Watter went on board the ship againâ€”Lyons told them to come on boardâ€”I went aboard alsoâ€”I don't believe any of the men were below in the hold when we came on board againâ€”they went down into the hold before we went into the boat; they were down in the hold when we first went into the boatâ€”I could not see what they were doingâ€”it was the carpenter, Lyons, and Carlos, who went belowâ€”they were below in the hold when I first went into the boatâ€”when we came back they were on deckâ€”I don't remember any more going down into the hold besides Lyons, Carlos, and the carpenterâ€”when we came back, I went on the deck of the ship; they did not all go out of the boat; the steward would not come out, and Powell stopped in the boatâ€”Lyons asked the steward to come on deck, and he would notâ€”Lyons and Duranno then began to throw bottles of wine at him, and they struck him with some of the bottles, and he went out of the boatâ€”I don't know whether they knocked him out of the boat or notâ€”he got into the waterâ€”I heard him crying out to Lyons for help when he was in the waterâ€”Lyons said he would not help him, for he had deceived him before, and he said it was too easy a death for himâ€”he was drownedâ€”I went down into the boat after the steward went out of it, and I did not go on board any moreâ€”I went on shore in the same boat that I first got into.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ATKINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say the steward was drownedâ€”was the wind in towards shore at that time? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I did not see him drownedâ€”the vessel went down shortly afterwardsâ€”when I saw Lyons talking to the second-mate, I saw that he had a cut across the face; he was bleeding a littleâ€”he had two cutsâ€”I don't remember on which side of his faceâ€”he had one on his face, and one on his lipâ€”it was a cut with a knifeâ€”when I saw Lopez in the cabin there were others thereâ€”it was near 6 o'clock when I saw the rope put round the captain's bodyâ€”I am quite sure that it was Lopez did thatâ€”Lyons was there at the timeâ€”I don't recollect any others besides those twoâ€”I was standing beside the captain's body at the timeâ€”the second-mate was sitting in the cabinâ€”he could see what passedâ€”Lyons assisted the second-mate in navigating the shipâ€”Lyons seemed to have the command of the ship amongst the menâ€”he seemed to be spokesmanâ€”he was the only man amongst them who could speak English properly.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you left the vessel in the boat, who was in the boat with you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Andersen, the carpenter, Powell, Watter, Chancis, and Marcelino when we left the ship to go ashoreâ€”when we first left the ship, the second-mate, Watter, Powell, the cook, the steward, and myself were in the boat; not Carlosâ€”he was not in the boatâ€”I saw the carpenter, Lyons, and Carlos go down into the holdâ€”that was not long before we left the vesselâ€”they did not go down into the cabinâ€”they went down forward, down the fore-hatchâ€”I was then on the main-deckâ€”I don't recollect what I was doingâ€”I don't remember who else was about the fore-hatchâ€”I don't remember seeing anyâ€”I don't remember who it was that called our boat backâ€”somebody called out of the other boat for us to come back.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. DALEY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> At the time the bottles that you speak of were thrown, where were you? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was on the deck; there was a good deal of confusionâ€”they were making a noiseâ€”I was not leaning over the sideâ€”I was standing close beside Lyons after I had come out of the</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010053"></xptr>
               <p>boatâ€”I saw where the bottles fellâ€”I was standing close to the ship's side, close to the bulwarksâ€”I could see into the boat.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SOLICITOR-GENERAL</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you able to see whether any of the bottles struck the steward? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes, they didâ€”the fore-hatch that I saw Lyons, Carlos, and Anderson go down, does not lead to any berths, or apartments; it leads down to the hold of the vessel.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ATKINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> In what language did Lyons speak to the steward when he was in the water? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He spoke in Englishâ€”the steward was not an Englishmanâ€”he was a Malayâ€”I know Lopez well (<hi rend="italic">pointing him out</hi>)â€”he did not assist in the navigation with the second-mate, that I know of.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18640201-name-150" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-150" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-150" type="surname" value="CANDEREAU"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-150" type="given" value="FRANK"></interp>FRANK CANDEREAU</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">through an interpreter</hi>). I am a Frenchmanâ€”I was a seaman on board the Flowery Landâ€”I was in the habit of sleeping in a house on the deckâ€”I slept in the same part of the house as Andersen, the carpenter, and Earlyâ€”some days before the captain was killed, I received a communication from Frank Powellâ€”I communicated that to the captainâ€”I recollect the morning that the captain was killed, but I don't know the dateâ€”I was woke up about 3 or half-past 3 in the morning by the carpenter and little <hi rend="italic">Jemmy</hi> (Early)â€”they were quite trembling, and the carpenter was cryingâ€”they did not give me any direction, they only told me to go to the wheelâ€”I did soâ€”when they came and awoke me, I asked them if it was 4 o'clockâ€”they said, "No; but you go to the wheel"â€”as I was going to the wheel, I saw the prisoners all together in a lot, but as it was dark at the time I could not exactly distinguish, but everybody was thereâ€”seven or eight of them had hand-spikes or capstan-bars in their handsâ€”I did not speak to themâ€”I only spoke to Frank Powellâ€”he told me that two were in the water; the captain's brother and the first-mateâ€”I asked after the captain, and he said, "Look here; there is death in the cabin;" pointing with his fingerâ€”I looked down in the cabin where they were in the habit of eatingâ€”I looked through the little window which is close to the compass, close to where the man at the wheel stands, and I saw the captain, dead, lying stretched out in the roomâ€”Frank Powell had not any weapon in his hand at that timeâ€”I afterwards went into the cabin when it was daylight, and saw the body of the captain wrapped up in canvasâ€”a rope was thrown over some part of the body, and it was hauled up, and thrown into the waterâ€”I helped to haul it up, and Watter, and another; I don't know who it wasâ€”Watter said to me, "If thou dost not lend a hand, take care of thyself"â€”at that time a great number of persons were in the cabin, but I can't say who they wereâ€”the room was full of bloodâ€”after the captain had been thrown into the water the cabin was washed a little, and then the boxes were all broken open to see what they containedâ€”I observed three persons doing thatâ€”Marco Watter, <hi rend="italic">Joe</hi> Catalan (Lopez), and Ambrosio (Duranno)â€”I saw some money taken out, and put upon the tableâ€”<hi rend="italic">Joe</hi> Catalan said the second-mate was to divide it; to share the moneyâ€”he said he was to divide the money amongst all the persons on boardâ€”I did not hear any of the others say any<lb></lb>thing about the division of the moneyâ€”afterwards the second-mate was told to share it into seventeen partsâ€”the money was then shared into seventeen parts; after that, all the day long, eating and drinking went onâ€”after that it was the second-mate who navigated the shipâ€”I know that three days after the murder he was spoken to about it, but I do not under<lb></lb>stand English sufficiently to know what was saidâ€”some days after the captain was murdered, I was in the room where I slept, and Basilio Delos</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010054"></xptr>
               <p>Santos came inâ€”that is him standing up nowâ€”he sharpened his knife, and said, "In two or three days I kill thee"â€”I will say it in Englishâ€”he said, "That is a knife; in two or three days we kill thee"â€”I said, "Well; kill me"â€”he said nothing more then, but he once told me, "This knife will serve thee as they have done to the captain"â€”he only said that onceâ€”he spoke in Spanishâ€”I remember when land was seenâ€”I can't exactly say at what time it was, but it was dark; it was not daylightâ€”we turned the ship aboutâ€”she was brought back againâ€”I got into a boatâ€”that was about midnight, I can't say exactlyâ€”Santos and Carlos were in the boat with meâ€”nobody else at that momentâ€”a little while after, Cassa, the lamp-trimmer, came down into the boatâ€”those who were in the ship called himâ€”I heard themâ€”Lyons was one, <hi rend="italic">Joe</hi> Catalan, (Lopez) Ambrosio Duranno, and Blancoâ€”they called him on board the ship againâ€”he went up on board the shipâ€”I remained in the boatâ€”I heard Cassa cry out in English, "Finish me quick"â€”he was down in the cabin when he said thatâ€”Lyons, <hi rend="italic">Joe</hi> Catalan, Blanco, and Ambrosio were on board the ship at that timeâ€”I after<lb></lb>wards saw the steward in the waterâ€”after we landed, the second-mate and I went to Rocha, and found a great quantity of Frenchmen thereâ€”we went to the campâ€”the prisoners did not know of our goingâ€”we met with a man who could speak English.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KEMP</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Can you speak Spanish? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No; I understand a few wordsâ€”I do not understand any conversation in Spanish that is addressed to meâ€”when the conversation took place between me and Santos, he addressed me in Spanish; both timesâ€”all he said was in Spanishâ€”I could understand all that he said to meâ€”I understood sufficient Spanish for thatâ€”I can tell you the words he made use of (<hi rend="italic">repeating them in Spanish</hi>)â€”I do not speak Spanish wellâ€”I had no other conversation with Santosâ€”I remember the distribution of the moneyâ€”Santos was not present on that occasion.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18640201-name-151" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-151" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-151" type="surname" value="ANDERSEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-151" type="given" value="MICHAEL"></interp>MICHAEL ANDERSEN</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">through an interpreter</hi>). I am a native of Norwayâ€”I was carpenter on board the <hi rend="italic">Flowery Land</hi>â€”the captain did not like the crewâ€”I heard him say so on deck, because they were not able to do their workâ€”I have seen the captain strike some of the crew, the steward, the cook, the lamp-trimmer, and Marco Watter; he struck Watter with his flat hand at the side of the headâ€”I did not see that more than onceâ€”the captain said to him at the time, "You are come aboard my ship as able seamen, and you cannot do your work, and when you are in China you will expect your pay"â€”I have seen the first-mate strike Basilio (Santos) with a rope; not so as to hurt himâ€”I remember when the captain was killed; about 2 o'clock that morning the boy, Early, came and woke me upâ€”I went on deckâ€”I saw the chief-mate lying close to the step leading to the poopâ€”he asked me who I wasâ€”I told him I was the carpenterâ€”he asked me to help him into the cabinâ€”I got him on the poopâ€”I found that his arm was broken, and his face was smashed to piecesâ€”he asked me to go and fetch the captainâ€”as I was turning to do so, I received a blow on the head with a hand-spike, or capstan-barâ€”I could not see who it was that struck meâ€”Marcelino after<lb></lb>wards spoke to me about being struckâ€”he said, "Me strike you"â€”I can't remember how long that was after I was struck; it was not the same morningâ€”I had a stiff neck for two or three days from the effects of the blowâ€”I fell by reason of the blow, and I then went into my berthâ€”I was called up again about half-past 5 or 6â€”I saw some of the captain's clothes ransacked in the cabinâ€”they were all there then, except the man at the wheelâ€”I saw the captain's body thrown overboardâ€”Blanco and Watter, and I believe, the Frenchman helped in thatâ€”before I came on deck after</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010055"></xptr>
               <p>I had turned in, they came and told me that they were going to kill the captain and the second-mateâ€”they were outside the door at the time they told me thisâ€”the door was openâ€”I saw Watter, Basilio, and Carlosâ€”there were more, but I can't say who they wereâ€”they are all I now recollect.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Who was the first person you mentioned? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Francisco, Blanco, Marco Watter, and George Carlos.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WELSBY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Bid you see any person pulling the rope up the com<lb></lb>panion ladder? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I did not see itâ€”the rope was down before I came on deckâ€”I saw Francisco, Marco Watter, and the Frenchman hauling itâ€”one of them called upon me to help them; I don't remember whichâ€”it was not the Frenchman, it was one of the other twoâ€”I did not help them, because the rope was covered with bloodâ€”as the body was being thrown overboard they told me it was the captain's body; they said, "There goes the captain, he will never more call us sons of bitches"â€”I don't remember who it was said thatâ€”it was either Blanco or Watter; it was not the Frenchmanâ€”I was afterwards called down into the cabinâ€”I saw money on the tableâ€”I saw it shared by the second mate into seventeen partsâ€”Watter told him only to share it into eight partsâ€”Lyons said that it ought to be shared between the lotâ€”there were some desks broken open before I came downâ€”I broke open a chest by the direction of Watter and the lot of themâ€”I believe it was Watter who gave me the direction, but they were all round meâ€”there were boots and shoes in the chest, and they took and helped themselvesâ€”I remember when we spoke the English vessel, the <hi rend="italic">Friends</hi>â€”on that day I saw five or six of the prisoners sitting on the fore-hatch talking together in Spanishâ€”they were Lyons, Watter, Blanco, and some others; I cannot name the othersâ€”I believe they were quarrellingâ€”I could see by their behaviourâ€”I could understand that they were talking about the carpenter and the second mateâ€”the Spanish words for them are "carpentero" and "piloto"â€”shortly after that I heard Lyons say in English, "If you like to kill the second mate and the carpenter you can do it; I shan't do it"â€”Lyons was speaking to the lot of them when he used those wordsâ€”Lyons afterwards told me that I must look out sharp, and do what these men told me to do, if I wanted to be safeâ€”on a subsequent day I remember Basilio and Watter coming to my room to sharpen their knives on my whetstone, and they told me in a very short time they would kill meâ€”the pair of them said soâ€”they said they were going to kill the steward and the Frenchman as wellâ€”Watter told me that he had killed sixteen beforeâ€”I remember the morning that we first made the landâ€”on that day I received orders from Lyons to have my tools ready, besides a candle and matches, to make a hole in the shipâ€”the lot of them were all together at the timeâ€”they had told me about a week before that I was to scuttle the shipâ€”they were all together thenâ€”in consequence of that being said to me, I had got a lot of oakum and a lot of plugs readyâ€”I thought they were going to leave me in the ship, and to save my own life I was going, after they left the ship, to stop the holes in the shipâ€”on the night that Lyons gave me the orders to make the hole, Carlos had first given me the order between 6 and 7 in the evening, but the other men said it was too soonâ€”between 10 and 11 at night I received orders from Joe Lyons to go down into the holdâ€”about five of the prisoners went down with meâ€”there were Carlos, Lyons, Blanco, Mauricio, and Frank Powellâ€”they had got sling shot and two knives each, and I think they had got the captain's revolverâ€”I know the men were in possession of the captain's revolverâ€”I bored some holes, four forward and four aftâ€”after that had been done we all went up on deckâ€”Lyons told me to go in the boat as soon as possibleâ€”I did soâ€”I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010056"></xptr>
               <p>heard persons calling from the ship to the steward to come on deckâ€”on that same afternoon, before I scuttled the ship, Lyons told me to fasten down the hatchways and everything that was loose on deckâ€”he told me to use long nailsâ€”I did not fasten the things downâ€”I cut all the lashings off, so that they might floatâ€”I did not use long nails; I took them as short as possible in order that if anybody was below they might come upâ€”I remember our coming up with a steamerâ€”the prisoners were very frightened if the steamer should see themâ€”Joe Catalan [<hi rend="italic">Lopez</hi>] said if the steamer should see them, the best thing was to jump overboard.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ATKINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How long was it after the death of the captain that Lyons said, "If you like to kill the second mate and the carpenter you may do it, but I won't?" <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I believe it was the same day that we spoke the English shipâ€”I believe that Lyons assisted those two men not to be killed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You say you heard some men out<lb></lb>side your berth; how many were there altogether? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I cannot tell; it was dark, and I was hiding myself in the cornerâ€”Watter came and called the Frenchman out, and Francisco stood at the door alongside of Watter at the timeâ€”the Frenchman was with me, and Watter came in and called him outâ€”I saw Basilio there tooâ€”they were passing backwards and forwards by the doorâ€”I said there were about fourâ€”I do not understand Spanishâ€”I understand a little Englishâ€”what was said about going to kill the captain was spoken in English.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KEMP</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Santos cannot speak English, can he? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I don't knowâ€”I don't know that name at allâ€”Basilio speaks English very littleâ€”when Santos and Watter spoke to me, they always talked English to meâ€”when they said they were going to kill the steward and the French-man, that was said in Englishâ€”I cannot remember the English words they made use ofâ€”I can undertake to say that the threat was that they would kill meâ€”they said, "By and by we will kill you"â€”I don't remember the words they used about the captain and the stewardâ€”it was Watter and Basilio who said, "By and by we will kill you"â€”it was not the same day; one said it one day, and another the otherâ€”Basilio said it first when he sharpened his knifeâ€”I can't remember how long that was after the captain had been murderedâ€”no one was present on the occasionâ€”I had no other conversation with Basilio.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You speak about the persons coming to your berth, do you recollect Carlos knocking and asking for admittance? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Noâ€”I have very often sat with Carlos in my berth for a considerable timeâ€”I did so the morning the captain was killed; he was in and outâ€”he did not sit with me for some considerable timeâ€”he did not come into my berth to hide from the other menâ€”I did not hear any of these men desire Carlos to throw the chief mate overboard, and he refused to do soâ€”he was in my berth that morning for two or three minutes; then he went out, and then he came in for two or three minutes, and then he went out againâ€”I and Carlos were not alone in my berthâ€”Early was with meâ€”I can't remember whether the door was shut at the timeâ€”I cannot remember whether he was there considerably more than two or three minutesâ€”he told me he was afraidâ€”he did not tell me that he had been desired to throw the mate's body overboard and had refused to do so.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. WELSBY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was it you who told Carlos you were afraid, or did Car<lb></lb>los tell you he was afraid? <hi rend="italic">A. I</hi> don't remember that I had any conversation with Carlos at all that morning, except that he told me he was afraidâ€”that</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010057"></xptr>
               <p>was after the captain was killed; after the carpenter had been and assisted the mate to the cabin; after the mate was killedâ€”he told me that he was afraid that the other men would kill him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> How many names do you remember of those who came to your door and said they were going to kill the captain and second mate? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There were Watter and Francisco, who told me about it, and Carlosâ€”I cannot remember any more that told me about it, but I remember I saw Basilio thereâ€”I remember fourâ€”there were those four there, but I can<lb></lb>not say which of them spokeâ€”that was after the first mate was killedâ€”I believe it was before the captain was killedâ€”it was after the first mate was killed that Carlos came in and out of my berth, and after he told me they were going to kill the captainâ€”I could not give an alarm to the cap<lb></lb>tain because I was struck down.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> What was it that Carlos said to you? was it that the other men were going to kill the captain, or that he and the others were going to kill the captain, how was it? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> He said he was afraid these men would kill himâ€”I cannot remember who of them told me they were going to kill the captain and the second mate, but I expect it was Marco Watter.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18640201-name-152" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-152" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-152" type="surname" value="WILLIAMS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-152" type="given" value="JOE"></interp>JOE WILLIAMS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">through an interpreter.</hi>) I was an ordinary seaman on board the <hi rend="italic">Flowery Land</hi>â€”I was in the second mate's Watch, from 8 to 12â€”I kept the watch from 8 to 12 the night the captain was killedâ€”I went to bed as soon as my watch was overâ€”I don't know many persons were in the deck-house when I went to bed, because it was very darkâ€”Powell, the Austrian, was there; I saw him in bedâ€”I was not awoke by anything during the nightâ€”I heard no noise in the nightâ€”I got up at 6 in the morn<lb></lb>ingâ€”I was awake about an hour before thatâ€”I remember Duranno coming into the deck-houseâ€”he said, "I killed the mate"â€”that was about 5 o'clockâ€”I did not hear the mateâ€”I did not hear any one in the waterâ€”after saying "I killed the mate," Duranno went out of the deck-house, and I went outâ€”I saw Francisco and the restâ€”they were saying, "We are going <hi rend="italic">aft</hi> to kill the captain"â€”he had nothing in his hand when he said thatâ€”I did not see any of them with anything in their handsâ€”I did not see what they were doing; they went aftâ€”Francisco told me something that same dayâ€”he did not say it to me, but he was saying it to the restâ€”he said, "I stabbed the captain three times, and the captain's brother also; I stabbed him three times;" and Marco Watter was saying the sameâ€”he said, "Three times I stabbed the captain"â€”Chancis said, "I have done the same," or "I helped them at the same time"â€”Lyons was not then present; he went into the cabin; I did not hear him say anything about itâ€”I have told everything that was saidâ€”Chancis told me, "1 struck the fire to see where the captain was"â€”he did not say where he struck the light, or where he got the matches to strike the light withâ€”Watter said, "The captain's brother was very light, because I threw him overboard with my own hand"â€”I don't know who gave orders after the captain was killed.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. ATKINSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Where did the conversation take place between Lopez and the other two men? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> In the forecastle; the house on deckâ€”I am quite sure I have told all that was saidâ€”Lopez did not say, "I helped to take the captain out of the cabin when he was dead."</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you taken into custody on this charge? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; I was sent over to this country in custodyâ€”I did not come the same as the othersâ€”I came in the same vessel, but I was on deckâ€”I was in custodyâ€”I was alone on deckâ€”I was taken in custody to the Police-court, and then dischargedâ€”I was not asked to give evidence</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010058"></xptr>
               <p>against these men after my dischargeâ€”I don't know who asked me to give my evidenceâ€”I don't know where it was takenâ€”I don't know the name of the house I went toâ€”I was asked to say what I knew about the matter<lb></lb>that was about a week after I was discharged from custody.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you not in your berth, in the house on the deck, and did not Duranno come to your berth, and call you out? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yesâ€”he did not shout out for me to get up; I was upâ€”when I came out of my berth, I did not see that Duranno was in a state of great excitement and alarmâ€”I don't know whether he spoke as if he was alarmed and frightenedâ€”he did not take hold of me and pull me, or ask me to follow him on deckâ€”I did not follow him on deckâ€”he went out; I don't know where he wentâ€”I did not find the mate alive on deck when I went on deckâ€”I did not see him at allâ€”I saw nothing.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BEST</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When the conversation took place which you have told us, and it was mentioned that two persons had stabbed the captain three times, was anybody else present except yourself, or the prisoners, or some of them? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> There were more persons there; Marcelino, Watter, Carlos, Santos, Ambrosio, and Chancisâ€”I think nobody else; I could not tell.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18640201-name-153" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-153" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-153" type="surname" value="POWELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18640201-name-153" type="given" value="FRANK"></interp>FRANK POWELL</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">through an interpreter.</hi>) I was a seaman on board the <hi rend="italic">Flowery Land</hi>â€”on the night of 10th September, I was on the first watchâ€”I turned in at 12 o'clockâ€”the first mate succeeded me, and came onâ€”I don't know what time it was when I got up next morning, but I think it was about half-past 3â€”I got up so early, because I heard some noise on deckâ€”it was a noise of somebody screeching on deckâ€”nobody called meâ€”when I got up I saw the chief mate on the starboard side, on deckâ€”he was groaningâ€”I did not go up to himâ€”Andersen, the carpenter, came upâ€”the chief mate was then lying in the same placeâ€”the carpenter went to himâ€”the chief mate told him to help him into his berthâ€”he did soâ€”I saw somebody run after the carpenter; I could not tell who it was, because it was darkâ€”he had a hand-spike in his hand, and I saw him strike the car<lb></lb>penter with it on the back of his neckâ€”the carpenter ran forwards, and I ran after him, under the gallant forecastleâ€”I went to the wheel soon after that; about 4 o'clockâ€”Candereau was at the wheel at that timeâ€”I was with him for about ten minutes; after that I went to the cabinâ€”the whole of the crew were thereâ€”I did not see Taffer, the second mate, there thenâ€”I heard him afterwards crying in his own cabin, and I heard Lyons call him outâ€”he came out and said, "What are you going to do with me? are you going to kill me?"â€”Lyons said, "No"â€”I did not hear him say anything elseâ€”I heard him afterwards tell him to take the vessel to some port where they could get clearâ€”that was on deckâ€”I did not see the captain's body hauled up, or know who hauled it upâ€”I remember the money being dividedâ€”after it was divided I heard the men talking in the forecastleâ€”I heard Francisco Blanco say, "I have killed the mate," and Duranno said, "I had a heaver; I first struck him and felled him on the deck"â€”it was then that Blanco said, "After I saw you strike him, I took the handspike and struck him on the head"â€”Watter said, after they killed the mate he was in the cabin with Joe Lyons, Francisco Blanco, and Joseph Chancis; they struck a light to see where the captain was sleeping; Joe Lyons was keeping the candle, and Marco Watter, Joseph Chancis, and Francisco Blanco, they stabbed the captain, the whole three of them"â€”when that was said by Watter the whole gang was in the forecastle; they could hear itâ€”the whole of the prisoners were in the forecastleâ€”Lyons was there; the whole of them</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010059"></xptr>
               <p>that were sleeping in the house on deck; Lyons, Blanco, Duranno, Santos, Carlos, Watter, and Chancis, I don't know the name of the other; it was Marcelino; he was thereâ€”I also saw Marcelino in the cabin when they went to the second mateâ€”at the time Watter said what I have stated, these men did nothing; only were laughingâ€”I heard Lyons tell the second mate to take them to some port, so that they could get clearâ€”the mate asked him, "Where do you want me to take the ship?"â€”he replied "Wherever you think it is better"â€”I remember going into the boat.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Were you also brought as a prisoner to this country charged with this offence? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; when they took these prisoners they took meâ€”I was taken to the Police-courtâ€”I had a share of the money, and the clothesâ€”I drank the champagne every day almostâ€”they had it on deck, and it was there for any one to drink; every one had it; not the second mate; the carpenter didâ€”the conversation about killing the mate and the captain was in Spanishâ€”I understand Spanishâ€”Watter spoke in Spanish (<hi rend="italic">the witness repeated it in Spanish.</hi>)</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. SLEIGH</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Can you write? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No. <hi rend="italic">Adjourned Thursday, February</hi> 4<hi rend="italic">th</hi>, 1864.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. METCALFE</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">submitted that the indictment was not sustained, inasmuch as the jurisdiction of the Court was not shown; the jurisdiction would depend upon whether or not this was a British ship; for the purpose of proving that, the prosecution had put in a certificate of registry, under</hi> 17 <hi rend="italic">and</hi> 18 <hi rend="italic">Vic. c.</hi> 104, <hi rend="italic">sec.</hi> 107; <hi rend="italic">that certified copy, he was prepared to admit, was to be received as proper proof of the contents of the registry, and if it had recited that this was a British ship, or that the owner was a British subject, it would be sufficient; but it nowhere did so; section</hi> 18 <hi rend="italic">provided that no ship should be deemed to be a British ship unless she belonged wholly to natural born subjects, to persons made denizens by letters of denization, or to a body corporate; if either of those classes of persons was shown to be the owner, it was to be deemed a British ship provided it was registered; but the registration did not make it so; that was a sine qua non; upon the face of the certificate itself, it appeared that the ship was built in America, and for aught that appeared the owner might be an American; his name and address only was given, without any description of him as a British subject or a naturalized person; the certificate also showed that the vessel was the subject of a certificate of sale, and he contended that even if it was a British ship at the time of registration, the prosecution ought to go further, and show that the power of sale had not been exercised in favour of any but a British subject; upon both these grounds he submitted the prosecution had failed to show any jurisdiction in this Court.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. RIBTON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">urged the same objection, and</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. KEMP</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">further submitted that there was no evidence to show that the certificate referred to the identical ship on board which this mutiny took place.</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. BARON BRAMWELL</hi>.â€”"<hi rend="italic">I am of opinion that there is nothing in the objection, but that there is abundant evidence to go to the Juryâ€”to say nothing of the presumption that a ship could not be registered if it had not been a British ship, and that the authorities had properly informed themselves of that matter, the owner is described in the certificate as" Wm. Weemys Kerr, of</hi> 25, <hi rend="italic">Poultry, in the City of London, merchant; "that is a British name, and the name of a person residing in the United Kingdom, and surely if John Jones or John Smith is described as living in a certain place in the City of London, there is a presumption that he is a natural born subject. But besides that, there is abundant evidence; she sails from the Port of London with an English name on her, with an English captain on board, with two English mates, and an Englishman, the brother of the captain; at least, persons bearing</hi>
               </p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="186402010060"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">English names, and speaking the English language. In addition to that, there is a piece of evidence furnished by the prisoners themselves on this subject, viz., their request that the ship may not be taken to any place where there were English authorities; which would imply that such a place would be one where they would be most in danger. I am of opinion, therefore, that there is abundant evidence</hi> (<hi rend="italic">whether it is inevitably proved is another matter</hi>) <hi rend="italic">upon which the Jury may find that this was a British ship. As to the other objection, that there is no evidence that the Flowery Land, named in the certificate, is the Flowery Land in question, that is for the Jury: we have it that this particular ship was a British ship, in addition to which it has been held over and over again, that identity of name is abundant evidence of identity of the thing. The only thing I was about to look at further, was whether there was any statement in the certificate of who the captain was; I do not see it; but it is a matter of perfect indifference, because, independently of that, there is abundant evidence, to my mind, that the ship is the ship named in the certificate, and independently of the certificate, there is other evidence upon which the Jury might well come to the conclusion that this was a British ship. However, if the Solicitor-General entertains any doubt upon the matter, and desires to give further evidence, he can do so." The</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">SOLICITOR-GENERAL</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">considered the evidence as it stood perfectly conclusive; but as the managing owner of the vessel was in attendance, he would call him.</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
